Here is a console app that executes your MSBuild file.
<pre style="BACKGROUND: #dddddd; WIDTH: 100%">
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Text;
using Microsoft.Build.BuildEngine;

namespace MSbuildproj
{
    class Program
    {
        [STAThread]
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            // Instantiate a new Engine object
            Engine engine = new Engine();

            // Point to the path that contains the .NET Framework 3.5 tools
            engine.BinPath = @"c:\windows\microsoft.net\framework\v3.5";


            // Instantiate a new FileLogger to generate build log
            FileLogger logger = new FileLogger();

            // Set the logfile parameter to indicate the log destination
            logger.Parameters = @"logfile=build.log";

            // Register the logger with the engine
            engine.RegisterLogger(logger);

            // Build a project file
            bool success = engine.BuildProjectFile(@"C:\build.proj");

            //Unregister all loggers to close the log file
            engine.UnregisterAllLoggers();

            if (success)
                Console.WriteLine("Build succeeded.");
            else
                Console.WriteLine("Build failed. View build.log for details");            

        }
    }
}
</pre>
I wrote this, this morning in about 5 minutes with the help of the MSDN docs. 
Now that is a very simple little program that executes your MSBuild project file.
Now what you can add is turn this into a Windows Form App and set the time at which 
it runs. Maybe even put it in the Notification Area. Remember to add the references
Microsoft.Build.Engine and Microsoft.Build.Framework in your project. One other thing
add a Application Configuration File to you project and add the following markup.
<pre style="BACKGROUND: #dddddd; WIDTH: 100%">
&lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?&gt;
